Taking into account the constraints imposed by SecAgg, we characterize the fundamental communication cost required to obtain the best accuracy achievable under Îµğœ€\varepsilon central DP (i.e. under a fully trusted server and no communication constraints). 1 Introduction

Federated learning (FL) is a widely used machine learning framework where multiple clients collaborate in learning a model under the coordination of a central serverÂ (McMahan etÂ al., 2017a; Kairouz etÂ al., 2021b). One of the primary attractions of FL is that it provides data confidentiality and can provide a level of privacy to participating clients through data minimization: the raw client data never leaves the device, and only updates to models (e.g., gradient updates) are sent back to the central server. This provides practical privacy improvements over centralized settings because updates typically contain less information about the clients, because they are more focused on the learning task, and also only need to be held ephemerally by the server

However, this vanilla federated learning does not provide any formal or provable privacy guarantees. To do so, FL is often combined with differential privacy (DP)Â (Dwork etÂ al., 2006b). This can be done in one of two ways111Local DP is yet another alternative, but it incurs higher utility loss and is therefore not typically used in practice.: 1) perturbing the aggregated (local) model updates at the server before updating the global model, or 2) perturbing each clientâ€™s model update locally and using a cryptographic multi-party computation protocol to ensure that the server only sees the noisy aggregate. The former is referred to as central DP, and it relies on the clientsâ€™ trust in the server because any sensitive information contained in the model updates is revealed to and temporally stored on the server. The latter is referred to as distributed DP (Dwork etÂ al., 2006a; Kairouz etÂ al., 2021a; Agarwal etÂ al., 2021, 2018), and it offers privacy guarantees with respect to an honest-but-curious server. Thus, a key technology for formalizing and strengthening FLâ€™s privacy guarantees is a secure vector sum protocol called secure aggregation (SecAgg)Â (Bonawitz etÂ al., 2016; Bell etÂ al., 2020), which lets the server see the aggregate client updates but not the individual ones.

Despite enhancing the clientsâ€™ privacy, aggregating model updates via SecAgg drastically increases the computation and communication overheadsÂ (Bonawitz etÂ al., 2016, 2019). This is even worse in federated settings where communication occurs over bandwidth-limited wireless links, and the extra communication costs may become a bottleneck that hampers efficient training of large-scale machine learning models. For example,Â Kairouz etÂ al. (2021a) reports that when training a language model with SecAgg and DP, even with a carefully designed quantization scheme, each client still needs to transmit about 161616 bits per model parameter each round. Moreover, the bitwidth needs to be scaled up when the privacy requirements are more stringent. This behavior disobeys the conclusion ofÂ Chen etÂ al. (2020) (derived under local DP), which shows that the optimal communication cost should decay with the privacy budget, i.e., data is more compressible in the high privacy regime.

Furthermore, because the server aggregates the model updates via SecAgg, we can only compress the model updates locally using linear schemes. This constraint rules out many popular compression schemes such as entropy encoders or gradient sparsification (Aji & Heafield, 2017; Lin etÂ al., 2017; Wangni etÂ al., 2017; Havasi etÂ al., 2018; Oktay etÂ al., 2019) etc., as these methods are non-linear.

Therefore, it is unclear whether or not the communication cost of SecAgg reported inÂ Kairouz etÂ al. (2021a); Agarwal etÂ al. (2021, 2018) is fundamental. If not, what is the smallest communication needed to achieve distributed DP with secure aggregation to achieve the same performance as in the centralized DP setting?

In this paper, we answer the above question, showing that the communication costs of existing mechanisms are strictly sub-optimal in the distributed mean estimation (DME) task (Suresh etÂ al., 2017) (see SectionÂ 4 for details). We also propose a SecAgg comaptible linear compression scheme based on sparse random projections (AlgorithmÂ 2), and then combine it with the distributed discrete Gaussian (DDG) mechanism proposed byÂ Kairouz etÂ al. (2021a). Theoretically, we prove that our scheme requires O~â€‹(minâ¡(n2â€‹Îµ2,d))~ğ‘‚superscriptğ‘›2superscriptğœ€2ğ‘‘\tilde{O}\left(\min(n^{2}\varepsilon^{2},d)\right) bits per client, where nğ‘›n is the per-round number of clients. This cost is significantly smaller than the communication cost of previous schemes which was O~Î´â€‹(dâ€‹logâ¡(d/Îµ2))subscript~ğ‘‚ğ›¿ğ‘‘ğ‘‘superscriptğœ€2\tilde{O}_{\delta}(d\log(d/\varepsilon^{2})) bits per client222For simplicity, we use the O~Î´â€‹(â‹…)subscript~ğ‘‚ğ›¿â‹…\tilde{O}_{\delta}\left(\cdot\right) notation to hide the dependency on Î´ğ›¿\delta and logâ¡nğ‘›\log n. To give perspective, (1) nğ‘›n is usually on the order of 103superscript10310^{3} per round due to the computational overhead of SecAgg, and (2) Îµğœ€\varepsilon is the privacy budget for a single round, i.e., Îµâ‰ˆÎµğ–¿ğ—‚ğ—‡ğ–ºğ—…/Rğœ€subscriptğœ€ğ–¿ğ—‚ğ—‡ğ–ºğ—…ğ‘…\varepsilon\approx{\varepsilon_{\mathsf{final}}}/{\sqrt{R}} if there are Rğ‘…R training rounds. Thus, for practical FL settings where large models are trained with SecAgg over many rounds, n2â€‹Îµ2superscriptğ‘›2superscriptğœ€2n^{2}\varepsilon^{2} is typically (much) smaller than dğ‘‘d.

We complement our achievability results with a matching lower bound, showing that to obtain an unbiased estimator of the mean vector, each client needs to communicate Î©~â€‹(minâ¡(n2â€‹Îµ2,d))~Î©superscriptğ‘›2superscriptğœ€2ğ‘‘\tilde{\Omega}(\min(n^{2}\varepsilon^{2},d)) bits with the server. Our upper and lower bounds together specify the fundamental privacy-communication-accuracy trade-offs under SecAgg and DP.

In addition, we show that with additional sparsity assumptions, we can further improve both the accuracy and communication efficiency while achieving the same privacy requirement, leading to a logarithmic dependency on dğ‘‘d.

Empirically, we verify our scheme on a variety of real-world FL tasks. Compared to existing distributed DP schemes, we observe 101010x or more compression with no significant decrease in test-time performance. Moreover, the compression rates can be made even higher with tighter privacy constraints (i.e., with smaller Îµğœ€\varepsilon), complying with our theoretical O~(min(n2Îµ2,d)\tilde{O}(\min(n^{2}\varepsilon^{2},d) communication bound.

Organization

The rest of this paper is organized as follows. We summarize related work in SectionÂ 2 and introduce necessary preliminaries in SectionÂ 3. We then provide a formal problem formulation in SectionÂ 4. Next, we present and analyze the performance of our main scheme (in terms of privacy, utility, and communication efficiency) and prove its optimality in SectionÂ 5.5. After that, we show, in SectionÂ 6.2, that with additional sparsity assumptions, one can simultaneously reduce the communication cost and increase the accuracy. Finally, we present our experimental results in SectionÂ 7 and conclude the paper in SectionÂ 8.

2 Related Work

SecAgg and distributed DP

SecAgg is cryptographic secure multi-party computation (MPC) that allows the server to collect the sum of nğ‘›n vectors from clients without knowing anyone of them. In our single-server FL setting, SecAgg is achieved via additive masking over a finite group (Bonawitz etÂ al., 2016; Bell etÂ al., 2020). However, the vanilla FL with SecAgg does not provide provable privacy guarantees since the sum of updates may still leak sensitive information (Melis etÂ al., 2019; Song & Shmatikov, 2019; Carlini etÂ al., 2019; Shokri etÂ al., 2017). To address this issue, differential privacy (DP) (Dwork etÂ al., 2006a), and in particular, DP-SGD or DP-FedAvg can be employed Song etÂ al. (2013); Bassily etÂ al. (2014); Geyer etÂ al. (2017); McMahan etÂ al. (2017b). In this work, we aim to provide privacy guarantees in the form of RÃ©nyi DP (Mironov, 2017) because it allows for accounting end-to-end privacy loss tightly.

We also distinguish our setup from the local DP setting (Kasiviswanathan etÂ al., 2011; Evfimievski etÂ al., 2004; Warner, 1965), where the data is perturbed on the client-side before it is collected by the server. Local DP, which allows for a possibly malicious server, is stronger than distributed DP, which assumes an honest-but-curious server. Thus, local DP suffers from worse privacy-utility tarde-offsÂ (Kasiviswanathan etÂ al., 2011; Duchi etÂ al., 2013; Kairouz etÂ al., 2016).

Model compression, sketching, and random projection

There has been a significant amount of recent work on reducing the communication cost in FL, see Kairouz etÂ al. (2019). Among them, popular compression approaches include gradient quantization (Alistarh etÂ al., 2017; Bernstein etÂ al., 2018), sparsification (Aji & Heafield, 2017; Lin etÂ al., 2017; Wangni etÂ al., 2017), and entropy encoders (Havasi etÂ al., 2018; Oktay etÂ al., 2019). However, since these schemes are mostly non-linear, they cannot be combined with SecAgg where all the encoded messages will be summed together. Therefore, in this work, we resort to compression schemes with linear encoders. The only exception are sketching based methods (Rothchild etÂ al., 2020; Haddadpour etÂ al., 2020). Our work differs from them in three aspects. First, we consider FL with privacy and SecAgg, whereas Rothchild etÂ al. (2020) only aims at reducing communication. Second, although we use the same count-sketch encoder, our decoding method is more aligned with the sparse random projection (Kane & Nelson, 2014). In the language of sketching, we decode the sketched model updates by â€œcount-meanâ€ instead of count-median, which improves space efficiency, thus requiring less memory to train a real-world large-scale machine learning model. We note that both count-sketch and random projection provides the same worst-case â„“2subscriptâ„“2\ell_{2} error bounds.

FL with SecAgg and distributed DP

The closest works to ours are cpSGDÂ (Agarwal etÂ al., 2018), DDGÂ (Kairouz etÂ al., 2021a), and SkellamÂ (Agarwal etÂ al., 2021), which serve as the main inspiration of this paper. However, all of these methods rely on per parameter quantization and thus lead to Î©~â€‹(d)~Î©ğ‘‘\tilde{\Omega}\left(d\right) communication cost. In this work, however, we show that when dâ‰«n2â€‹Îµ2much-greater-thanğ‘‘superscriptğ‘›2superscriptğœ€2d\gg n^{2}\varepsilon^{2}, we can further reduce dimensionality and achieve the optimal communication cost O~â€‹(n2â€‹Îµ2)~ğ‘‚superscriptğ‘›2superscriptğœ€2\tilde{O}(n^{2}\varepsilon^{2}) in this regime. Our scheme also demonstrates 101010x or more compression rates (depending on the privacy budget) relative to the best existing distributed DP schemes.

4 Problem Formulation

We start by formally presenting the distributed mean estimation (DME) Suresh etÂ al. (2017) problem under differential privacy. Note that DME is closely related to the federated averaging (FedAvg) algorithm McMahan etÂ al. (2017a), where in each round, the server updates the global model using a noisy estimate of the mean of local model updates. Such a noisy estimate is typically obtained via a DME mechanism, and thus one can easily build a DP-FedAvg scheme from a DP-DME scheme.

Distributed mean estimation under differential privacy

Consider nğ‘›n clients each with a data vector xiâˆˆâ„dsubscriptğ‘¥ğ‘–superscriptâ„ğ‘‘x_{i}\in\mathbb{R}^{d} that satisfies âˆ¥xiâˆ¥2â‰¤csubscriptdelimited-âˆ¥âˆ¥subscriptğ‘¥ğ‘–2ğ‘\left\lVert x_{i}\right\rVert_{2}\leq c (e.g., a clipped local model update). After communicating with nğ‘›n clients, a server releases a noisy estimates Î¼^^ğœ‡\hat{\mu} of the mean Î¼â‰œ1nâ€‹âˆ‘ixiâ‰œğœ‡1ğ‘›subscriptğ‘–subscriptğ‘¥ğ‘–\mu\triangleq\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i}x_{i}, such that 1) Î¼^^ğœ‡\hat{\mu} satisfies a differential privacy constraint (see DefinitionÂ 3.1 and DefinitionÂ 3.2), and 2) ğ”¼â€‹[âˆ¥Î¼^âˆ’Î¼âˆ¥22]ğ”¼delimited-[]subscriptsuperscriptdelimited-âˆ¥âˆ¥^ğœ‡ğœ‡22\mathbb{E}\left[\left\lVert\hat{\mu}-\mu\right\rVert^{2}_{2}\right] is minimized. The goal is to design a communication protocol (which includes local encoders and a central decoder) and an estimator Î¼^^ğœ‡\hat{\mu}.

In this paper, we consider two different DP settings. The first is the centralized DP setting: the server has access to all xisubscriptğ‘¥ğ‘–x_{i}â€™s, i.e., Î¼^=Î¼^â€‹(x1,â€¦,xn)^ğœ‡^ğœ‡subscriptğ‘¥1â€¦subscriptğ‘¥ğ‘›\hat{\mu}=\hat{\mu}\left(x_{1},...,x_{n}\right). For a fixed privacy constraint, the fundamental problem we seek to solve is: what is the smallest communication cost under the distributed DP setting needed to achieve the accuracy of the centralized DP setting? Further, we seek to discover schemes that (a) achieve the optimal privacy-accuracy-communication trade-offs and (b) are memory efficient and computationally fast in encoding and decoding.

Remark 5.5.

Notice that in this work, we are mostly interested in unbiased estimators due to the following two reasons: 1) it largely facilities the convergence analysis of the SGD based methods, as these types of stochastic first-order methods usually assume access to an unbiased gradient estimator in each round. 2) In the high-dimensional or high-privacy regimes where dâ‰«n2â€‹Îµ2much-greater-thanğ‘‘superscriptğ‘›2superscriptğœ€2d\gg n^{2}\varepsilon^{2}, the MSE is not the right performance measure since an estimator can have a large bias while still achieving a relative small MSE. 6 Sparse DME with SecAgg and DP

TheoremÂ 5.2 in SectionÂ 5.5 specifies the optimal trade-offs of private DME for all possible datasets xnsuperscriptğ‘¥ğ‘›x^{n}. In other words, it provides a worst-case (over all possible xisubscriptğ‘¥ğ‘–x_{i}) bound on the utility and shows that AlgorithmÂ 2 is worst-case optimal. However, we show in this section that with additional assumptions on the data, it is possible to improve the trade-offs beyond what is given in TheoremÂ 5.2.

One such assumption is sparsity of the data, which is justified by several empirical results that gradients tend to be (or are close to being) sparse. We hence study the sparse DME problem, which is formulated as in SectionÂ 4 but with an additional sğ‘ s-sparsity assumption on Î¼ğœ‡\mu, i.e., âˆ¥Î¼âˆ¥0â‰¤ssubscriptdelimited-âˆ¥âˆ¥ğœ‡0ğ‘ \left\lVert\mu\right\rVert_{0}\leq s. We present a sparse DME algorithm adapted from AlgorithmÂ 2, showing that by leveraging the sparse structure of data, one can surpass the lower bound in TheoremÂ 5.2. Moreover, the dependency of communication cost and MSE on the model size dğ‘‘d becomes logarithmic.

7 Empirical Analysis

We run experiments on the full Federated EMNIST and Stack Overflow datasetsÂ (Caldas etÂ al., 2018), two common benchmarks for FL tasks. The are over 108superscript10810^{8} data samples unevenly distributed across N=342477ğ‘342477N=342477 clients. On both datasets, we select nâˆˆ[100,1000]ğ‘›1001000n\in[100,1000] and R=1500ğ‘…1500R=1500. Quantization or dimensionality reduction?

Though we achieve significant compression rates from our linear dimensionality reduction technique, we now explore how these results compare with compression via quantization. Theoretically our bound can achieve a minimum compression independent of the ambient gradient size dğ‘‘d. Because of this, we also expect our methods to outperform those based on quantization because their communication scales with dğ‘‘d.

Our results in FigureÂ 3 and TableÂ 1 corroborate this hypothesis. We compare our compression against conditional randomized rounding to an integer grid of field size 2bsuperscript2ğ‘2^{b}. (2021a), we find that we can only compress to 101010 bits per parameter on SONWP; if we instead favour our linear dimensionality reduction technique, we achieve a much lower 1.21.21.2 bits per parameter (with r=10ğ‘Ÿ10r=10x and b=12ğ‘12b=12). For F-EMNIST, we find we can compress down to 0.240.240.24 bits per parameter at z=0.5ğ‘§0.5z=0.5 by optimizing both bğ‘b and rğ‘Ÿr; this is much lower than using only quantization (101010 bits per parameter) and a marginal increase over only dimensionality reduction (0.270.270.27). We observe 0.70.70.7 bits per parameter at z=0.3ğ‘§0.3z=0.3 and 1.21.21.2 at z=0.1ğ‘§0.1z=0.1. 8 Conclusion

In this paper, we study the optimal privacy-communication-accuracy trade-offs under distributed DP via SecAgg. We show that existing schemes are order optimal when dâ‰ªn2â€‹Îµ2much-less-thanğ‘‘superscriptğ‘›2superscriptğœ€2d\ll n^{2}\varepsilon^{2} and strictly sub-optimal otherwise. To address this issue, we provide an optimal scheme that leverages sparse random projections. We also show how our scheme can be minimally modified when the client updates are sparse to further improve the trade-offs. Our extensive experiments on FL benchmark datasets demonstrate significant communication gains (âˆ¼similar-to\sim10x) relative to existing schemes. Many important questions remain open, including obtaining a fundamental characterization of the privacy-accuracy-communication trade-offs under other models of distributed DP (e.g. via a trusted third-party or in a secure enclave as in Bittau etÂ al. (2017); Ghazi etÂ al. (2020b, 2021, c, a); Ishai etÂ al. (2006); Balle etÂ al. (2019, 2020); Balcer & Cheu (2020); Balcer etÂ al. (2021); Girgis etÂ al. (2021b, a); Erlingsson etÂ al. (2019)).

A.1 Impact of cohort size

Finally, we explore how varying the number of clients per round (or, cohort size) nğ‘›n impacts the privacy-utility-communication tradeoff. This value plays several key roles in this tradeoff. First, increasing nğ‘›n increases the sampling probability of the cohort, which increases the total privacy expenditure. However, it also tends to improve model performanceâ€”this may mean that a higher noise multiplier zğ‘§z can be chosen so as to instead decrease the total privacy cost (this is typically the case when N is large enough, e.g., SO). In terms of communication, TheoremÂ 5.2 suggests that increasing nğ‘›n will also increase the per-client comunication. Because of the aforementioned complex tradeoffs, we (approximately) fix the privacy budget Îµğœ€\varepsilon and only perturb nğ‘›n minimally around a nominal value of 100100100. In FigureÂ 8, we see that dependence of communication on nğ‘›n is observed empirically as well.

In addition to this impact on rğ‘Ÿr, setting nğ‘›n can also have a significant impact on the run time of SecAgg, of Oâ€‹(nâ€‹logâ¡(n)â€‹d)ğ‘‚ğ‘›ğ‘›ğ‘‘O(n\log(n)d). For large values of nğ‘›n, this can entirely prevent the protocol from completing. Because a practitioner desires the most performant model, a common goal is the increase nğ‘›n so as to obtain a tight Îµğœ€\varepsilon (due to a now higher zğ‘§z) with the least cost in performance. But, because large nğ‘›n can crash SecAgg, this places a constraint on the maximum nğ‘›n that can be chosen. Since our methods compress the updates (dğ‘‘d above), it is possible to still increase nğ‘›n so long as we increase rğ‘Ÿr accordingly (by n2n1â€‹logâ¡n2logâ¡n1subscriptğ‘›2subscriptğ‘›1subscriptğ‘›2subscriptğ‘›1\frac{n_{2}}{n_{1}}\frac{\log{n_{2}}}{\log{n_{1}}} where n2>n1subscriptğ‘›2subscriptğ‘›1n_{2}>n_{1}), which maintains fixed runtime. If the resulting model at higher nğ‘›n achieves higher performance, then we observe a net benefit from this tradeoff. For a practical privacy parameter or z=0.6ğ‘§0.6z=0.6, our results in TableÂ 8 suggest that this may be possible. Specifically, increasing nğ‘›n from 100â†’1000â†’1001000100\to 1000 and settings r=50â€‹x>15â€‹xğ‘Ÿ50ğ‘¥15ğ‘¥r=50x>15x accordingly, we observe that the final model with n=1000ğ‘›1000n=1000 clients achieves a nearly 555pp gain. We observe that z<0.3ğ‘§0.3z<0.3 cannot meet these requirements.

A.2 Attempting to improve compression via per-layer sketching and thresholding

We attempted two additional methods to improve our compression rates. First, we noticed that the LSTM models we trained had consistently different â„“2subscriptâ„“2\ell_{2} norms across layers in training. Because these norms are different, we hypothesizes that sketching and perturbing them separately may improve the model utility. We attempt this protocol in FiguresÂ 9 andÂ 10, where FigureÂ 9 uses z=0.05ğ‘§0.05z=0.05 and Figure10 uses z=0ğ‘§0z=0. We find that, in general, there are no significant performance gains. We further attempt to threshold low values in the sketch. Because this leads to a biased estimate of the gradient, we keep track of the zero-d values in an error term. We tried several threshold values and we found that this as well led to no significant performance gains.
